# Plot the correlation matrix as a heatmap
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 8))
sns.heatmap(correlation_df2, annot=True, cmap='coolwarm', fmt=".2f", linewidths=0.5)
plt.title('Figure 1 : Correlation matrix of Decathlon sports features')
plt.savefig('Correlation Matrix of Decathlon Sports Features', dpi= 300)
plt.show()

Each cell in the heatmap shows the correlation coefficient (Pearson's r) between two events. It ranges from:

+1: perfect positive correlation (as one increases, so does the other)

-1: perfect negative correlation (as one increases, the other decreases)

0: no linear correlation

How to read the heatmap:

Diagonal (from top-left to bottom-right): Always 1.00 — each event is perfectly correlated with itself.

Color intensity:

  • Red = strong positive correlation

  • Blue = strong negative correlation

  • White/neutral = near 0, little or no correlation

Positive Correlations:

100m ↔ 110m Hurdles (0.58)

  • Athletes who perform well in 100m also tend to do well in 110m hurdles.

Poids ↔ Disque (0.62)

  • Strength-based events: strong throwers in one tend to do well in the other.

Hauteur ↔ Poids (0.49)

  • Moderate correlation between strength and jumping ability (not always intuitive, but might reflect athlete body type).

Negative Correlations:

100m ↔ Longueur (-0.60)

  • Surprisingly strong negative correlation. This might be due to the scoring system or data quality (could be worth reviewing).

100m ↔ Disque (-0.22)

  • Faster athletes don’t necessarily throw the discus far (makes sense—different muscle groups and skills).

400m ↔ Longueur (-0.60)

  • Sprinters may trade-off between explosive jumps and mid-distance endurance.

In [30]:
# Calculating the quality of representation (cos²) for each individual
cos2_2 = (X_pca ** 2).sum(axis=1) / (X_scaled ** 2).sum(axis=1)

# Normalizing the cos² values to scale bubble sizes
cos2_2_normalized = (cos2_2 - cos2_2.min()) / (cos2_2.max() - cos2_2.min())
In [31]:
# Plotting the factorial plane with bubble sizes proportional to cos²

# Adding the athletes' names to the plot
for i, name in enumerate(decathlon_df['Athlete']):

# 5. Précisez les avantages et inconvénients respectifs des méthodes kmeans et CAH.

# 5. Specify the respective advantages and disadvantages of the kmeans and CAH methods.
In [ ]:
# K-means and Classification Ascendant Hierarchique (CAH) are two popular unsupervised classification techniques, 
# often used to group data into clusters. Here is a comparison of the advantages and disadvantages of each method:


    # 1. k-means


        # Advantages :
        
            # Simplicity and efficiency: K-means is a simple method to implement and generally quick to run, even on large datasets.

            # Scalability: It works well with large datasets and can be easily extended to handle millions of points.

            # Easy to interpret: K-means results are often easy to interpret, as each point clearly belongs to a single cluster.

            # Suitable for spherical clusters: K-means works well when clusters have a spherical or isotropic shape, i.e. 
            # when they are similar in size and shape.


        # Disadvantages :


            # Sensitivity to initial values: K-means results can vary depending on the initial values of the cluster centres. 
            # It is often necessary to repeat the algorithm with different initializations.

            # Number of clusters to be defined: K-means requires the number of clusters to be specified in advance, which can be a disadvantage 
            # if the optimal number of clusters in the data is not known.

            # Sensitivity to outliers: Outliers or extreme values can distort clusters, as K-means 
            # uses the Euclidean distance, which is sensitive to extreme values.

            # Irregularly shaped clusters: It is not suitable for data where clusters have complex or irregular (non-spherical) shapes.


    # 2. Hierarchical Ascending Classification (HAC)


        # Advantages :


            # No need to specify the number of clusters: Unlike K-means, HAC does not require the number of clusters to be defined in advance. 
            # It produces a complete hierarchy of clusters (dendrogram) and allows you to choose the number of clusters according to the similarity threshold.

            # Suitable for complex shapes: CAH can identify clusters of various shapes and sizes, making it more flexible than K-means 
            # for non-linear data.

            # Intuitive visualisation: The dendrogram generated by HAC makes it easy to visualise the structure of the data and to determine the number 
            # of clusters visually.


        # Disadvantages :


            # Computational complexity: HAC is often slower than K-means, especially for large datasets, as it requires computing 
            # all distances between points.

            # Limited scalability: It is not well suited to very large datasets, as its complexity increases rapidly with the size of the dataset. 
            # of the dataset.

            # Sensitivity to small perturbations: Once a junction is made between clusters, it cannot be modified, which makes the method 
            # the method sensitive to small errors in the data or outliers.


# Comparison of Methods


    # Number of clusters:
        # K-Means: Must be specified in advance	
        # CAH: Chosen after construction of the dendrogram

    # Cluster shape :	
        # K-Means: Spherical	
        # CAH: Can be complex in shape

    # Scalability :	
        # K-Means: Very scalable for large datasets	
        # CAH: Limited scalability, slow for large datasets


    # Robustness to outliers :
        # K-Means: Sensitive	
        # CAH: Less robust if outliers influence initial mergers

    # Interpretation :	
        # K-Means: Easy to interpret but depends on initialization	
        # CAH: Intuitive with dendrogram visualisation

# When should each method be used?


    # K-means is preferable when :
        # You have a large volume of data.
        # You already know how many clusters you want.
        # Clusters have a spherical shape and similar sizes.

    # CAH is preferable when :
        # You don't have a clear idea of the number of clusters.
        # You want to explore the structure of the data.
        # Clusters are complex and non-linear.

# Each method therefore has its advantages and disadvantages depending on the nature of the data and the objectives of the analysis.

# This graph is a visualization of K-means clustering on the factorial plane (Principal Component 1 and Principal Component 2) based on the decathlon 
# athletes' performance. Here’s a breakdown of the elements and the interpretation:


    # Clusters:

        # The graph displays 5 clusters, as expected (clusters 0 to 4), and they are color-coded based on their cluster label.
        # Each athlete is represented by a point, and their name is labeled on the graph.
        # The color legend on the right side clearly shows how the different clusters are colored:
        # Cluster 0: Purple
        # Cluster 1: Blue
        # Cluster 2: Teal
        # Cluster 3: Green
        # Cluster 4: Yellow


    # Centroids:

        # The red 'X' markers represent the centroids of the clusters. These are the central points for each cluster and help to visualize 
        # where the "center" of each group lies.
        #There are 5 centroids, one for each cluster, which is correct given the 5-cluster configuration of the K-means algorithm.


    # Athletes’ Placement:

        # Athletes like Sebrle, Clay, and Karpov are placed in Cluster 4 (yellow), which is located to the left of the plane.
        # Casarsa is a standout case in Cluster 2 (teal), placed far in the top-right of the factorial plane, indicating a unique performance 
        # profile relative to the others.
        #The spread of athletes across the plane suggests the distribution of their performance metrics after PCA reduction. For instance, 
        # athletes in Cluster 1 (blue) seem to have more diverse placements but still share some performance similarity.


    # Cluster Compactness:

        # Some clusters, such as Cluster 4 (yellow) and Cluster 1 (blue), appear more compact, suggesting that athletes within these groups have 
        # more similar performance metrics.
        # Other clusters, like Cluster 2 (teal) and Cluster 0 (purple), are more spread out, suggesting greater variation in performance within those clusters.


    # Analysis of Cluster Characteristics:

        # Cluster 4 (Yellow): Contains athletes such as Sebrle, Clay, and Karpov. These athletes might have a similar overall performance profile 
        # based on their relative positions.
        # Cluster 2 (Teal): Contains athletes like Casarsa, who appears to have an outlier performance compared to others in the cluster, 
        # indicating that this athlete performs uniquely.
        # Cluster 0 (Purple): Includes athletes like Warner and Drew. This group is positioned in the bottom-left quadrant, indicating that their performances 
        # have distinct characteristics compared to others.

## Knowing that i reduced the dimensionality to 5 components and kmeans clusters to 5 can we say this graph is accurate enough to display 
# the situation as it is even we had 10 components in the outset ?

# The graph I have created displays the results of clustering athletes on a two-dimensional plane derived from the first two principal components (PC1 and PC2) 
# after reducing the dimensionality to five principal components. You originally had 10 components (likely from 10 decathlon events), 
# but you've reduced it to 5 and visualized just 2 of them. Here's how we can interpret the accuracy of this representation:


    # 1. Dimensionality Reduction from 10 to 5 Components:

        # By reducing the original 10 components to 5 principal components using PCA, you are simplifying the data while trying to retain as much variance
        #  as possible. Typically, the first few principal components capture the most variance, meaning the most important patterns in the data are preserved.
        # However, five components may still carry significant information that is not fully captured when plotting only two components (PC1 and PC2). 
        # PC3, PC4, and PC5 may still explain a meaningful portion of the variance that’s not visible in this 2D plot.


    # 2. Visualization in 2 Dimensions (PC1 and PC2):

        # The current plot only visualizes data along PC1 and PC2, which may not capture all the patterns present in the data. Even though PC1 and PC2 
        # usually explain the majority of the variance, some important features might still exist in PC3, PC4, and PC5.
        # This means that while this graph is a useful simplified view of the data, it is not a complete representation of all relationships between athletes 
        # in the 5-dimensional PCA space. There may be overlap or misinterpretations because we’re not seeing the impact of the other components.


    # 3. K-Means Clustering on Reduced Components:

        # K-means clustering was performed using all 5 principal components, which means that the cluster formation took into account more dimensions 
        # than what you’re showing in this 2D plot.
        # The plot shows the projection of these clusters into the first two components, but the true structure of clusters is in 5 dimensions. 
        # Some athletes that appear close together in this plot might be farther apart in higher dimensions.


    # 4. Accuracy of the Graph:

        # Pros:

            # This graph provides a good high-level view of the athlete clusters and their groupings based on the most important sources of variation 
            # in the data (PC1 and PC2).
            # It simplifies the interpretation of athlete groupings and highlights the dominant patterns.

        # Cons:

            # The full structure of the clusters is not fully captured since you're only seeing the first two components.
            # Some nuances in the performance of athletes, especially those dependent on the higher principal components (PC3, PC4, PC5), might be missed.
            # The visual separation of clusters in this 2D plot may not reflect the true distances between points in the full 5D space, 
            # so some athletes might seem grouped closely but are actually more distinct in higher dimensions.


    # Conclusion:

        # This graph gives a simplified but useful approximation of the clustering result. It effectively shows the main patterns and relationships 
        # based on the most important sources of variation (PC1 and PC2). However, for full accuracy and understanding of the clustering and relationships 
        # between athletes, you would need to consider the other components as well.

        # To capture more detailed relationships, we could:

            # Plot the clusters along PC3 vs. PC4 to see how the clusters are distributed in other dimensions.
            # Use 3D visualization (e.g., PC1, PC2, and PC3) to give a richer picture of the cluster structure.

        # This graph is still quite effective for communicating the broad trends and relationships in the data, but keep in mind that it’s an approximation 
        # of the full 5-dimensional clustering.

# I selected 5 clusters using the following method. I observed the longest vertical lines in the dendrogram before they were cut by a horizontal line. 
# these were intersected by a horizontal line. Once I had determined which lines were the longest, I drew a dotted line 
# at the level of these lines. Finally I counted the number of lines cut by this new dotted line. It gave me the number of clusters
